            , which would make gate noise fully learnable up to small error. We develop an algorithm based on cycle benchmarking that fully learns gate-dependent Pauli noise channel assuming perfect initial state preparation, and experimentally demonstrate the method on IBM’s CNOT gate. Based on the experiment data, we conclude that this assumption is unlikely to be correct in our experiment as it gives unphysical estimates that are outside the feasible region we determined. Furthermore, we use the data to obtain a lower bound on the state preparation noise and conclude that it has the same order of magnitude as gate noise on the device we used. Therefore, the issue of unlearnability is a practically relevant concern, for which the noise on initial states is an important factor that cannot be neglected on current quantum hardware.

